I have all the data I need. The diagnosis is now fully formed. Here is the complete analysis and fix:

---

## Diagnosis

The bug is in `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`. The `.logo` element is an `inline-flex` container sitting as a **flex item** inside the `flex`-row `.navInner`. While `flex-shrink: 0` and `white-space: nowrap` are already present in the file (added during a prior partial-fix session), **the bug persists because those declarations are incomplete as a lockdown**. The defensive chain has two missing links:

1. **`.logo` has no explicit `min-width`**. Flex items have `min-width: auto` by default, which *normally* expands to hold nowrap content — but when the outer flex container (`navInner`) is under squeeze, the browser's flex algorithm can still compress `.logo`'s box below its content size under certain layout paths. The only unconditional guarantee is `min-width: max-content` on the flex item itself.

2. **`.navInner` has no `flex-wrap: nowrap` + `gap`-safe layout**. The `.links` side has `min-width: 0` (correct — lets the tagline yield), but there's no explicit declaration that the row itself must never wrap. Without `flex-wrap: nowrap` being unambiguous, combined with the logo not being sized to `max-content`, at very narrow widths both sides can re-participate in the flex shrink cycle.

The root cause is **AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text** — a flex identity element that has partial shrink protection but no `min-width: max-content` absolute floor, leaving the browser free to compress the element's layout box below its intrinsic text width under extreme squeeze.

---

## Root Cause

**AP-066** — The `.logo` flex item relies on `flex-shrink: 0` + `white-space: nowrap` as its defense, but `flex-shrink: 0` only prevents *proportional shrinking*; it does not set a hard minimum width. If the item's initial `flex-basis` (which defaults to `auto`, resolving to the element's natural width) is somehow computed narrower than the text (e.g. due to a nested `inline-flex` sizing edge case under heavy constraint), the text wraps. The fix is `min-width: max-content`, which is the *only* property that unconditionally tells the browser "this box is never narrower than its longest content line."

---

## Fix

### 1. `src/components/ui/Navigation/Navigation.module.scss`

Three targeted changes: add `min-width: max-content` to `.logo`, add `flex-wrap: nowrap` to `.navInner`, and harden the existing comments to reflect the principle.

```scss
.navInner {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  justify-content: space-between;
+ flex-wrap: nowrap; // Identity row never wraps — logo must always stay on one line
  max-width: $elan-container-wide;
  margin: 0 auto;
  padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-2x);

  @media #{$elan-mq-sm} {
    padding: var(--portfolio-spacer-1-5x) var(--portfolio-spacer-4x);
  }
}

.logo {
  display: inline-flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: $portfolio-spacer-0-5x;
  text-decoration: none;
- // The logo is the site's core identity line. It must never wrap or shrink
- // under flex pressure, even at the narrowest viewports. The tagline beside it
- // is allowed to absorb any overflow by wrapping to two lines.
- flex-shrink: 0;
+ // IDENTITY PRIORITY RULE (AP-066):
+ // The logo "Yilan Gao" is a non-negotiable identity element. It must render
+ // on a single line at every viewport width, without exception. flex-shrink: 0
+ // prevents proportional shrink; min-width: max-content is the hard floor —
+ // it tells the browser the box is never narrower than its longest content line,
+ // surviving any flex constraint from the parent. The tagline (.links) absorbs
+ // all remaining pressure by wrapping to two lines via -webkit-line-clamp: 2.
+ flex-shrink: 0;
+ min-width: max-content;
  @include transition-fast;

  &:hover {
    .logoMark {
      background-color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }

    .logoText {
      color: var(--portfolio-text-neutral-max);
    }
  }
}
```

`.logoText` already has `white-space: nowrap` — keep it as a redundant second layer of defense (belt-and-suspenders is correct here). No change needed there.

The `.links` side already has `min-width: 0` and `.tagline` already has `-webkit-line-clamp: 2` — those are correct and need no change. The tagline will compress freely while the logo holds.

### 2. `docs/design-anti-patterns.md` — amend AP-066, add the priority rule

Locate the existing AP-066 entry and amend it to codify the identity priority rule you've stated:

```markdown
<a id="ap-066"></a>
## AP-066: Unconstrained Flex Compression Breaking Identity Text

**Status: ACTIVE**

**Trigger:** A flex item containing identity text (logo, name, core brand line) uses only
`flex-shrink: 0` + `white-space: nowrap` as its wrap defense, without `min-width: max-content`.

**Why it's wrong:** `flex-shrink: 0` prevents *proportional* shrinking in the flex
algorithm but does not set a hard minimum width on the box. Under heavy squeeze,
the browser can still compute an initial `flex-basis: auto` that resolves narrower
than the text content, causing the text to wrap. `white-space: nowrap` prevents
line-breaks within the text node but does nothing to stop the layout box from being
compressed around it — the text overflows instead of wrapping, or the box itself
wraps as a unit within a multi-line flex container.

**Identity Priority Rule:**
> Any element that is a logo, personal name, or core identity line
> (navigation or otherwise) must NEVER wrap to two lines under viewport squeeze.
> This is unconditional — no breakpoint, no exception.
> Soft-content elements (taglines, blurbs, secondary identity copy) are the
> designated yield surface: they may wrap to two lines to absorb flex pressure.
> Hard-content elements (logo, name) yield nothing.

**Correct alternative:**
```css
/* Hard identity element — never compresses */
.logo {
  flex-shrink: 0;
  min-width: max-content; /* ← the unconditional floor; flex-shrink: 0 alone is insufficient */
}

/* Containing row never wraps */
.navInner {
  flex-wrap: nowrap;
}

/* Soft element — absorbs all remaining pressure */
.tagline {
  min-width: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  display: -webkit-box;
  -webkit-box-orient: vertical;
  -webkit-line-clamp: 2; /* yields gracefully to two lines */
}
```

**The correct defense is three-layer:**
1. `flex-wrap: nowrap` on the row — ensures the identity item and its sibling never stack vertically.
2. `flex-shrink: 0` on the identity item — removes it from proportional shrink allocation.
3. `min-width: max-content` on the identity item — sets the unconditional minimum box width to exactly the intrinsic content width. This survives any flex algorithm path.

**Seen in:** FB-146 (nav logo "Yilan Gao" wrapping to two lines under squeeze).
**Also affects:** Any nav, masthead, or branded header using a flex row with mixed hard/soft content.
```

---

## Principle

**Identity Priority Rule — Hard vs. Soft Content in Flex Rows**

When a flex row contains both identity-critical text (logo, name) and soft-content text (tagline, blurb), the pressure hierarchy is:

| Element class | Flex behavior | Under squeeze |
|---|---|---|
| **Hard** (logo, name) | `flex-shrink: 0` + `min-width: max-content` | Holds its intrinsic width unconditionally |
| **Soft** (tagline, blurb) | `min-width: 0` + line-clamp | Wraps gracefully to 2 lines, absorbs all pressure |

The row itself gets `flex-wrap: nowrap` so the flex algorithm is never given the option of stacking the two sides vertically — all yielding happens *within* the soft element, not at the row level. The "Designer, AI Systems & Experience…" tagline is the designated yield surface; "Yilan Gao" is not.
